courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, participants will:

1. understand the rationales and underpinning theories behind various learning design principles;

2. employ appropriate learning design approaches to supporting multiple ways of learning in face-to-face and online settings;

3. evaluate strengths and weaknesses of various learning design principles and approaches with respect to various educational contexts;

4. gain pedagogical knowledge and technological skills related to learning design in new and emerging educational contexts.

On successful completion of this course, students will be able to:

1. describe and explain the value of data and analytics for education;

2. identify appropriate tools and methods to measure and analyze educational data in different contexts;

3. apply the analytic methods and understanding to analyze data;

4. recognize participants’ privacy and rights.

On successful completion of this course, students will be able to:

1. understand design thinking and scientific inquiry, their phases and operation, and their application in practice;

2. understand how design thinking principles solve different problems in different contexts;

3. recognize the value of design thinking and scientific inquiry to organizations, economies and society;

4. apply the design thinking as scientific inquiry to create and manage projects.

On successful completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. describe and explain different literacies needed for digital citizens;
2. understand the importance of the digital citizenships competencies in different context;
3. design, develop and evaluate a digital citizenship education program.

On successful completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. describe and explain theories of educational technology innovation;
2. understand how to sustain educational technology development in communities;
3. design and develop an educational technology strategical plan.

After completing the course, students will have:

1. mastered the latest theoretical underpinning of innovative learning organizations and leadership;

2. gained insights into the dynamic relationship among innovation, learning organizations, and leadership;

3. investigated organizational innovations and innovative leadership from multiple perspectives through engaging in critical analysis of real-life examples;

4. developed the essential mindset and skillset that drive innovations and changes in different organizational settings.

Upon the completion of the course, students will be able to:

- Learn from other professionals in the field;

- Develop future career options / opportunities;

- Develop positive attitude and responsibility, and strong work ethics;

- Develop problem solving skills;

- Develop beneficial links with the Learning Design and Technology Industry;

- Demonstrate ability in the planning, implementation, and evaluation of a work task independently.

Upon completion of this course, students should be able to:

1. identify a critical issue that merits further investigation in the field of Learning Design and Technology;

2. integrate the content, knowledge, and skills from prior learning to address the issue concerned;

3. show their research, analytical, and higher order thinking skills during the research process; and

4. generate new understanding from their project findings to help develop their future profession.
